    "documents": [
      {
        "id": "be12d86a-7fc0-4dd2-8bfd-deaa0660abd2",
        "score": 0.65077055,
        "text": "The document outlines financial security requirements for Market Participants in the ERCOT region, focusing on enforcement levels and the release of financial security.\n\n1. **Financial Security Increase**: \n   - Market Participants must increase their financial security to at least 110% of their Total Potential Exposure (TPE) or any other liability to ERCOT within two Bank Business Days if they have already provided financial security.\n\n2. **Duration of Requirements**:\n   - Increased financial security requirements remain for a minimum of 60 days and continue until ERCOT decides to reduce them.\n\n3. **Level II Enforcement**:\n   - ERCOT will notify Market Participants to provide financial security at 115% of their TPE or other liabilities within two Bank Business Days. This requirement also lasts for a minimum of 60 days.\n\n4. **Level III Enforcement**:\n   - ERCOT will require financial security at 120% of TPE within two Bank Business Days, with excess security in the form of a cash deposit. This requirement lasts for a minimum of 90 days.\n\n5. **Release of Financial Security**:\n   - After terminating a Standard Form Market Participant Agreement, ERCOT retains financial security to cover potential future obligations.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-rag/ERCOT/protocol/ERCOT_Nodal_Protocols:_Section_16:_Registration_and_Qualification_of_Market_Participants/page_79.jpg",
          "page_num": 79,
          "title": "ERCOT Nodal Protocols: Section 16: Registration and Qualification of Market Participants",
          "year": "",
          "market": "ERCOT",
          "data_type": "protocol"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "bb0fa483-8011-4e26-8465-94449bbc9403",
        "score": 0.63328004,
        "text": "The document outlines the requirements for Counter-Parties regarding ERCOT Securitization Uplift Charge Initial Invoice Credit. \n\n1. **Credit Requirements**: Counter-Parties must maintain an escrow deposit equal to or above their Load-Allocated Securitization Uplift Charge Credit Exposure (LASUCCE). This deposit must be in a form acceptable to ERCOT.\n\n2. **Payment Breach**: If a Counter-Party fails to meet LASUCCE requirements, they are considered in Payment Breach, allowing ERCOT to suspend their rights or take other actions until compliance is achieved.\n\n3. **Suspension of Rights**: ERCOT's decision not to suspend rights on one occasion does not prevent future suspensions.\n\n4. **Means of Satisfying Requirements**: Counter-Parties can satisfy escrow deposit requirements by:\n   - Providing an unconditional, irrevocable letter of credit with ERCOT or TEMSFN as the beneficiary.\n   - Ensuring letters of credit are drawn on a U.S. domestic bank or a domestic office of a foreign bank.\n   - Adhering to issuer limits for letters of credit.\n   - Depositing cash with TEMSFN through ERCOT, allowing ERCOT to draw on these deposits for overdue payments. Cash deposits may earn interest payable to the Counter-Party, but ERCOT must have immediate access to the cash.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-rag/ERCOT/protocol/ERCOT_Nodal_Protocols:_Section_27:_Securitization_Uplift_Charges/page_14.jpg",
          "page_num": 14,
          "title": "ERCOT Nodal Protocols: Section 27: Securitization Uplift Charges",
          "year": "",
          "market": "ERCOT",
          "data_type": "protocol"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "98726ea3-9587-4c5a-b39b-262afc31ec94",
        "score": 0.63132083,
        "text": "The document outlines the procedures for monitoring a Counter-Party's Securitization Uplift Charge Credit Exposure by ERCOT. Key points include:\n\n1. **Monitoring Responsibility**: ERCOT is tasked with monitoring the credit exposure of each Counter-Party, specifically regarding Securitization Uplift Charge Credit Exposure.\n\n2. **Escrow Deposit Requirement**: Counter-Parties must maintain escrow deposits equal to or greater than their Securitization Uplift Charge Credit Exposure.\n\n3. **Notification and Compliance**: ERCOT will notify Counter-Parties if they need to increase their escrow deposits to comply with requirements.\n\n4. **Suspension Conditions**: ERCOT may suspend a Counter-Party if their exposure equals or exceeds 100% of their escrow deposit.\n\n5. **Failure to Maintain Deposits**: If a Counter-Party fails to maintain the required escrow deposits, ERCOT will notify them of the shortfall and provide deadlines for compliance:\n   - By 1500 on the second Bank Business Day if notified before 1500.\n   - By 1700 on the second Bank Business Day if notified after 1500 but before 1700.\n\n6. **Use of Financial Security**: If the Counter-Party does not comply, ERCOT may use Financial Security related to other market activities to cover the shortfall.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-rag/ERCOT/protocol/ERCOT_Nodal_Protocols:_Section_27:_Securitization_Uplift_Charges/page_18.jpg",
          "page_num": 18,
          "title": "ERCOT Nodal Protocols: Section 27: Securitization Uplift Charges",
          "year": "",
          "market": "ERCOT",
          "data_type": "protocol"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "d04ccb80-4f62-44ed-b269-2f579f542362",
        "score": 0.61151785,
        "text": "The document outlines procedures related to financial security requirements for Counter-Parties in the ERCOT market. Key points include:\n\n1. **Notification and Deadlines**: If a Counter-Party fails to maintain required financial security, ERCOT will notify them of the amount needed to increase their security. Deadlines for compliance are specified:\n   - By 1500 on the second Bank Business Day if notified before 1500.\n   - By 1700 on the second Bank Business Day if notified after 1500.\n\n2. **Consequences of Non-Compliance**: \n   - ERCOT will inform the QSE\u2019s Authorized Representatives and Credit Contact if security is not received by 1530 on the due date.\n   - Failure to notify representatives does not prevent ERCOT from exercising its rights.\n\n3. **QSE Designation**: If a QSE fails to increase its financial security, ERCOT may require the designation of a new QSE.\n\n4. **Payment Withholding**: ERCOT will withhold payments to the Counter-Party until financial security is increased. This includes various types of payments and credits.\n\n5. **Bid Rejection**: ERCOT may reject bids or offers in CRR Auctions and the DAM from Counter-Parties that have not increased their financial security.\n\n6. **Notification and Payment Release**: \n   - If security is increased by the deadline, ERCOT will notify each LSE and Resource.\n   - ERCOT will release any held payments once the security is increased as required.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-rag/ERCOT/protocol/ERCOT_Nodal_Protocols:_Section_16:_Registration_and_Qualification_of_Market_Participants/page_70.jpg",
          "page_num": 70,
          "title": "ERCOT Nodal Protocols: Section 16: Registration and Qualification of Market Participants",
          "year": "",
          "market": "ERCOT",
          "data_type": "protocol"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "6868c9f9-f08d-4fdb-8707-5f49890240e1",
        "score": 0.61126316,
        "text": "The document outlines the financial security requirements for counter-parties involved with ERCOT (Electric Reliability Council of Texas). Key points include:\n\n1. **Definitions**:\n   - **Financial Security**: Collateral posted with ERCOT in specified forms.\n   - **Remainder Collateral**: Financial Security minus various exposures and credit limits.\n   - **Ultimate Parent**: The top entity preparing consolidated financial statements.\n\n2. **Creditworthiness Requirements**:\n   - Counter-parties must meet ERCOT's credit standards and maintain Financial Security at or above their Total Potential Exposure (TPE).\n   - ERCOT can suspend rights if creditworthiness is not maintained, but failure to suspend does not waive future enforcement.\n   - ERCOT may use Financial Security to cover short-pays of specific charges if escrow deposits are insufficient.\n\n3. **Review of Counter-Party Eligibility**:\n   - ERCOT can review a counter-party's eligibility at any time to ensure compliance with registration and qualification requirements.\n   - Reviews can be triggered by changes reported by the counter-party, information discovered by ERCOT, or periodic reviews.\n   - Additional background checks may be conducted as part of the review process.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-rag/ERCOT/protocol/ERCOT_Nodal_Protocols:_Section_16:_Registration_and_Qualification_of_Market_Participants/page_40.jpg",
          "page_num": 40,
          "title": "ERCOT Nodal Protocols: Section 16: Registration and Qualification of Market Participants",
          "year": "",
          "market": "ERCOT",
          "data_type": "protocol"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "45538cbf-fce8-49f6-aa02-40a8feaa714f",
        "score": 0.6090795,
        "text": "The document outlines the protocols for handling Securitization Uplift Charges by ERCOT. Key points include:\n\n1. **Interest on Deposits**: Interest on cash deposits is calculated based on average balances and is not paid on balances held by TEMSFN. Annually, ERCOT returns earned interest to the Counter-Party if no obligations remain.\n\n2. **Purpose of Escrow Deposits**: These deposits are solely for collateralizing Securitization Uplift Charge Credit Exposure and cannot be used for other financial security obligations.\n\n3. **Deposit Management**: Deposits must be made to the designated account. ERCOT is not liable for misdirected funds, and incorrect deposits may result in late or non-payment charges.\n\n4. **Excess Cash**: Counter-Parties with excess cash can request its return from ERCOT.\n\n5. **Usage Restrictions**: Deposits are not used for periodic invoice payments unless there is an insufficient payment by the Invoice Recipient.\n\n6. **Cash Collateral**: Can be used for Securitization Uplift Charge Reallocation Invoices.\n\n7. **Excess Deposits**: Cannot cover insufficient payments for ERCOT market activities or additional financial security requests.\n\nThese protocols ensure proper management and allocation of funds related to Securitization Uplift Charges.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-rag/ERCOT/protocol/ERCOT_Nodal_Protocols:_Section_27:_Securitization_Uplift_Charges/page_15.jpg",
          "page_num": 15,
          "title": "ERCOT Nodal Protocols: Section 27: Securitization Uplift Charges",
          "year": "",
          "market": "ERCOT",
          "data_type": "protocol"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "3d39762e-dfce-4512-9d48-d88287482795",
        "score": 0.6086943,
        "text": "The document outlines procedures related to Securitization Uplift Charges within the ERCOT Nodal Protocols. It discusses the enforcement of financial security for short-paying Market Participants whose agreements have been terminated. If these participants cannot pay their dues, ERCOT will use any remaining escrow deposits to cover unpaid charges.\n\nSection 27.5 details the requirements for Securitization Uplift Charge Initial Invoice Escrow Deposits. It defines these deposits as amounts held by ERCOT in cash or irrevocable letters of credit to ensure payment obligations are met. The Texas Electric Market Stabilization Funding N LLC (TEMSFN) holds a secured interest in these deposits, which is perfected upon the deposit of cash or a letter of credit by a Counter-Party.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-rag/ERCOT/protocol/ERCOT_Nodal_Protocols:_Section_27:_Securitization_Uplift_Charges/page_13.jpg",
          "page_num": 13,
          "title": "ERCOT Nodal Protocols: Section 27: Securitization Uplift Charges",
          "year": "",
          "market": "ERCOT",
          "data_type": "protocol"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "b299383f-2b58-4a49-8bb4-6683f2374c27",
        "score": 0.60745883,
        "text": "The document outlines procedures for ERCOT's Transmission Security Analysis and Reliability Unit Commitment. Key points include:\n\n1. **Security Sequence**: ERCOT evaluates the need for resource-specific deployments to manage congestion in real-time operations.\n\n2. **Contingency Management**: ERCOT must post any contingencies removed from the standard list to the MIS Secure Area, including reasons for removal, within one hour.\n\n3. **Network Security Analysis (NSA)**: For each hour of the RUC Study Period, ERCOT analyzes all selected contingencies by:\n   - Performing full AC analysis.\n   - Monitoring element and bus voltage limit violations.\n   - Monitoring transmission line and transformer security violations.\n\n4. **Remedial Action Plans (RAPs)**: If available, RAPs must be used before considering resource commitments.\n\n5. **Security Violations Review**: ERCOT reviews all security violations before RUC execution.\n\n6. **Inclusion of RAS, AMPs, and RAPs**: These must be included in the contingency analysis within the Network Operations Model.\n\n7. **Contingency Deselection**: ERCOT may deselect contingencies causing errors or inconclusive results. An analysis is required to determine the cause, using Day-Ahead processes for support. Deselected contingencies must be posted with reasons within one hour.\n\n8. **NPRR1239 Update**: Upon system implementation, deselected contingencies will be posted to the ERCOT website instead of the MIS Secure Area.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-rag/ERCOT/protocol/ERCOT_Nodal_Protocols:_Section_5:_Transmission_Security_Analysis_and_Reliability_Unit_Commitment/page_14.jpg",
          "page_num": 14,
          "title": "ERCOT Nodal Protocols: Section 5: Transmission Security Analysis and Reliability Unit Commitment",
          "year": "",
          "market": "ERCOT",
          "data_type": "protocol"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "08d74f0b-4329-4de3-b120-0c52506cc026",
        "score": 0.60525054,
        "text": "The document outlines protocols related to Securitization Default Charges by ERCOT:\n\n**26.4 Securitization Default Charge Supporting Data Reporting:**\n1. ERCOT will post monthly data on the Market Information System (MIS) Certified Area, including:\n   - Securitization Default Charge Maximum MWh Activity (SDCMMA)\n   - Securitization Default Charge Maximum MWh Activity Total (SDCMMATOT)\n   - Securitization Default Charge Maximum MWh Activity Ratio Share (SDCMMARS)\n   - Counter-Party level components of the SDCMMA calculation.\n2. ERCOT will report Initial Settlement data as it becomes available and update it with Final Settlement data.\n\n**26.5 Securitization Default Charge Escrow Deposit Requirements:**\n\n**26.5.1 Securitization Default Charge Escrow:**\n1. Defines the escrow deposit as cash or an irrevocable letter of credit held by ERCOT for a Market Participant\u2019s obligation.\n2. ERCOT, as the servicer, requires escrow deposits to secure obligations, granting Texas Electric Market Stabilization Funding M LLC (TEMSFM) a secured interest.\n3. The security interest is perfected upon a Counter-Party\u2019s deposit of cash or a letter of credit with ERCOT.\n\n**26.5.2 ERCOT Securitization Default Charge Credit Requirements for Counter-Parties:**\n1. Counter-Parties must maintain their escrow deposit at or above their Securitization Default Charge Credit Exposure (SDCCE).\n2. Each Counter-Party must maintain the required escrow deposit in a form acceptable to ERCOT.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-rag/ERCOT/protocol/ERCOT_Nodal_Protocols:_Section_26:_Securitization_Default_Charges/page_12.jpg",
          "page_num": 12,
          "title": "ERCOT Nodal Protocols: Section 26: Securitization Default Charges",
          "year": "",
          "market": "ERCOT",
          "data_type": "protocol"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "c44081e0-eda7-4ca1-9c7c-7539c9e880f9",
        "score": 0.603194,
        "text": "The document outlines protocols related to Securitization Uplift Charges within the ERCOT Nodal Protocols. Key points include:\n\n1. **Escrow Deposit Requirements**: Counter-Parties may need to increase their Securitization Default Charge and Uplift Charge escrow deposits. ERCOT can allocate available financial security funds on a pro rata basis to meet these requirements.\n\n2. **Notification and Payment Conditions**: ERCOT must notify the QSE\u2019s Authorized Representative if the required security is not received by a specified time. ERCOT is not obligated to make payments to a Counter-Party unless the escrow deposit is increased to meet or exceed the required amount.\n\n3. **Payment Breach and Late Payments**: In cases of payment breaches or late payments by Market Participants, specific remedies are applicable as outlined in Section 16.11.6.\n\n4. **Release of Escrow Deposits**: Upon termination of a Market Participant\u2019s agreement, ERCOT retains the Securitization Uplift Charge escrow deposits to cover potential future obligations.\n\nThese protocols ensure financial security and compliance in the management of Securitization Uplift Charges.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-rag/ERCOT/protocol/ERCOT_Nodal_Protocols:_Section_27:_Securitization_Uplift_Charges/page_19.jpg",
          "page_num": 19,
          "title": "ERCOT Nodal Protocols: Section 27: Securitization Uplift Charges",
          "year": "",
          "market": "ERCOT",
          "data_type": "protocol"
        }
      }
    ]
  },
  "error": null,
  "metadata": {}
}

