      {
        "id": "08d74f0b-4329-4de3-b120-0c52506cc026",
        "score": 0.60525054,
        "text": "The document outlines protocols related to Securitization Default Charges by ERCOT:\n\n**26.4 Securitization Default Charge Supporting Data Reporting:**\n1. ERCOT will post monthly data on the Market Information System (MIS) Certified Area, including:\n   - Securitization Default Charge Maximum MWh Activity (SDCMMA)\n   - Securitization Default Charge Maximum MWh Activity Total (SDCMMATOT)\n   - Securitization Default Charge Maximum MWh Activity Ratio Share (SDCMMARS)\n   - Counter-Party level components of the SDCMMA calculation.\n2. ERCOT will report Initial Settlement data as it becomes available and update it with Final Settlement data.\n\n**26.5 Securitization Default Charge Escrow Deposit Requirements:**\n\n**26.5.1 Securitization Default Charge Escrow:**\n1. Defines the escrow deposit as cash or an irrevocable letter of credit held by ERCOT for a Market Participant\u2019s obligation.\n2. ERCOT, as the servicer, requires escrow deposits to secure obligations, granting Texas Electric Market Stabilization Funding M LLC (TEMSFM) a secured interest.\n3. The security interest is perfected upon a Counter-Party\u2019s deposit of cash or a letter of credit with ERCOT.\n\n**26.5.2 ERCOT Securitization Default Charge Credit Requirements for Counter-Parties:**\n1. Counter-Parties must maintain their escrow deposit at or above their Securitization Default Charge Credit Exposure (SDCCE).\n2. Each Counter-Party must maintain the required escrow deposit in a form acceptable to ERCOT.",
        "metadata": {
